> Why add ricotta cheese to pancakes? Because it makes them impossibly light and 
> tender. Their ethereal texture and lemony bounce will send you into your day 
> dreaming of clouds, sheep, and other fluffy-wuffy things. If anything brings 
> you back down to earth, it'll be the links of sausage on the side with their 
> big, bold, and meaty juices.

== Prepare Produce and Sausage ==

Wash and dry all produce. Preheat oven to 300 degrees. Zest @lemon{1} until you 
have 1 tsp zest, then halve and squeeze juice into a small #bowl{}. Slice 
@orange{1} into wedges.

Add @breakfast sausage{4%ounce} to a medium pan over medium-high heat. Cook until 
browned on all sides and cooked through, ~{7-10%minutes}. Reduce heat to low to 
keep sausage warm until rest of meal is ready.

== Make Pancake Batter ==

While sausage cooks, crack @eggs{2} into a large bowl. Add @sugar{3%tablespoon} 
and whisk vigorously until smooth. Whisk in @milk{2/3%cup}, then whisk in 
@ricotta cheese{4%ounce}. Add lemon zest and 3 TBSP lemon juice and stir to 
combine.

In a medium bowl, combine @nutmeg{1/4%teaspoon}, @salt{1/4%teaspoon}, 
@flour{1%teaspoon}, and @baking powder{1%teaspoon}. Add to bowl with egg mixture 
and stir until just combined.

> TIP: Don't overmix the ingredients—you should have a slightly lumpy batter.

== Cook Pancakes ==

Heat @vegetable oil{1%teaspoon} in a large pan (use a #nonstick pan{} if you 
have one). Working in batches, add batter ¼ cup at a time, making round 
pancakes. Cook until bottoms are golden brown and tops are bubbly, 
~{3-4%minutes}. Flip pancakes and cook until golden brown on other side, 
~{2-3%minutes} more. Transfer to a #baking sheet{} and place in oven to keep 
warm. Repeat until all batter is used.

== Serve ==

Divide pancakes between plates. Top each with a bit of @butter{1.5%tablespoon}.

> TIP: Add a drizzle of maple syrup, if you have it.

Serve with sausage and orange wedges on the side.